                        <td colspan="3" style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #ddd; text-align: center;">
                            <strong>Read DOWNWARD ‚¨áÔ∏è:</strong> <span style="font-size: 1.3em; color: #388e3c;">001</span>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                
                <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.1em;"><strong>Result:</strong> 4.125‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ = <span style="color: #1976d2; font-weight: bold;">100</span><span style="font-weight: bold;">.</span><span style="color: #388e3c; font-weight: bold;">001</span>‚ÇÇ</p>
            </div>

            <div class="step-box">
                <strong>Step 3: Normalize</strong><br>
                100.001‚ÇÇ = 1.00001 √ó 2¬≤<br>
                (We moved the binary point 2 places to the left)
            </div>

            <div class="step-box">
                <strong>Step 4: Calculate Exponent</strong><br>
                Actual exponent = 2<br>
                Stored exponent = 2 + 127 = 129‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ = 10000001‚ÇÇ
            </div>

            <div class="step-box">
                <strong>Step 5: Extract Mantissa</strong><br>
                From 1.00001, take fractional part: 00001<br>
                Pad to 23 bits: 00001000000000000000000
            </div>

            <div class="step-box">
                <strong>Final IEEE 754 Representation:</strong>
                <div class="bit-display">
<span class="sign-bit">1</span> <span class="exponent-bits">10000001</span> <span class="mantissa-bits">00001000000000000000000</span>
Sign  Exponent    Mantissa
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Decimal -4.125 = Binary -100.001 = IEEE 754: 1 10000001 00001000000000000000000</strong></p>
            </div>

            <div class="analogy-box">
                <h4>üí° Why This Method is Easier</h4>
                <p>The parallel conversion technique is like doing two tasks simultaneously instead of one after the other. You can see both parts developing side-by-side, which makes it easier to understand how the whole number comes together. Plus, you can spot patterns more easily!</p>
                <p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> For the fractional part, stop when you reach 1.0 or when you've done enough iterations for your required precision. Some fractions (like 0.1) never terminate in binary, just like 1/3 never terminates in decimal (0.333...)!</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Overflow and Underflow</h3>
            <p>An <strong>overflow</strong> occurs when the exponent is too large to be represented in the allotted bits. An <strong>underflow</strong> occurs when the exponent is too small to be represented.</p>

            <div class="analogy-box">
                <h4>üéÆ Real-World Example: Video Game Glitches</h4>
                <p>Ever heard of the Pac-Man "kill screen" at level 256? That's an overflow! The game used 8 bits to store the level number, which can only go up to 255. When it tried to go to level 256, it overflowed and caused glitches. The same thing happens with floating-point numbers when the exponent gets too large!</p>
            </div>

