            <h3>Common Mistakes and How to Avoid Them</h3>
            <div class="important-box">
                <h4>‚ö†Ô∏è Mistake #1: Forgetting the Implicit Leading 1</h4>
                <p>Remember: The mantissa always has an implicit "1." before it! If the mantissa bits are 10100000..., the actual mantissa is 1.10100000...</p>
            </div>

            <div class="important-box">
                <h4>‚ö†Ô∏è Mistake #2: Forgetting the Exponent Bias</h4>
                <p>Always subtract 127 from the stored exponent to get the actual exponent! If the exponent bits represent 130, the actual exponent is 130 - 127 = 3.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="important-box">
                <h4>‚ö†Ô∏è Mistake #3: Confusing Binary and Decimal Fractions</h4>
                <p>0.1 in binary is NOT 0.1 in decimal! Binary 0.1 = decimal 0.5. This is why 0.1 + 0.2 ‚â† 0.3 in many programming languages!</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Why Does This Matter?</h3>
            <div class="concept-box">
                <h4>üåç Real-World Applications</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Graphics & Gaming:</strong> 3D coordinates, colors, and physics calculations all use floating-point</li>
                    <li><strong>Scientific Computing:</strong> Simulating weather, modeling molecules, calculating orbits</li>
                    <li><strong>GPS & Navigation:</strong> Precise location coordinates require floating-point precision</li>
                    <li><strong>Financial Systems:</strong> Currency conversions and interest calculations</li>
                    <li><strong>Machine Learning:</strong> Neural networks use millions of floating-point calculations</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>



        <!-- Character Encoding -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>üî§ Character Encoding: Representing Text</h2>
            <p>We've learned how to represent numbers, but how do computers represent letters, symbols, and emojis? The answer is <strong>character encoding</strong>‚Äîa system that assigns a unique binary number to each character.</p>

            <div class="analogy-box">
                <h4>üéØ Analogy: Secret Code Books</h4>
                <p>Character encoding is like a secret code book where each letter has a corresponding number. If A=1, B=2, C=3, etc., then the word "CAB" would be "3-1-2". Computers use similar code books (called character sets) to convert between text and binary numbers!</p>
            </div>

            <h3>ASCII (American Standard Code for Information Interchange)</h3>
            <p><strong>ASCII</strong> is a structured system that facilitates communication between different computer systems by using 8 bits to represent characters in its coding scheme. It was one of the first widely-adopted character encoding standards.</p>

            <ul>
                <li>Uses <strong>7 bits</strong> for characters (128 possible characters)</li>
                <li>Includes uppercase letters (A-Z), lowercase letters (a-z), digits (0-9)</li>
                <li>Includes punctuation marks and control characters</li>
                <li>Example: 'A' = 65‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ = 01000001‚ÇÇ, 'a' = 97‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ = 01100001‚ÇÇ</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="concept-box">
                <h4>üí° Fun Fact About ASCII</h4>
                <p>The difference between uppercase and lowercase letters in ASCII is exactly 32! This is because bit 5 (the 32s place) is the only difference. 'A' = 65, 'a' = 97 (65 + 32). This made it easy for early computers to convert between cases by flipping a single bit!</p>
            </div>

            <h3>BCD (Binary-Coded Decimal)</h3>
            <p><strong>BCD</strong> is a numeric coding system used in the 1950s and 1960s. BCD is very common in electronics, and used to display numerical data, such as alarm clocks and calculators. BCD encodes each digit of a decimal number in a 4-bit binary form.</p>

            <p>For example, the decimal number 1234 in BCD would be: 0001 0010 0011 0100</p>

            <h3>EBCDIC (Extended Binary-Coded Decimal Interchange Code)</h3>
            <p><strong>EBCDIC</strong> was extended to an 8-bit code. Extended Binary-Coded Decimal Interchange Code (EBCDIC) was one of the first widely-used computer codes that supported upper and lowercase alphabetic characters, in addition to special characters, such as punctuation and control characters.</p>

            <h3>Unicode: The Modern Standard</h3>
            <p><strong>Unicode</strong> is a 16-bit alphabet that is downward compatible with ASCII because Unicode is 16 bits. It has the capacity to encode the majority of characters used in all of the world's languages. Unicode is currently the default character set of the Java programming language.</p>

            <div class="analogy-box">
                <h4>üòä Real-World Example: Emojis!</h4>
                <p>Ever wonder how emojis work? They're part of Unicode! Each emoji has a unique Unicode code point. For example, üòä (smiling face) is U+1F60A. Unicode can represent over 1 million different characters, including emojis, Chinese characters, Arabic script, mathematical symbols, and more. That's why you can text emojis to friends around the world!</p>
            </div>

            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Encoding</th>
                    <th>Bits</th>
                    <th>Characters</th>
                    <th>Usage</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>ASCII</td>
                    <td>7-8</td>
                    <td>128</td>
                    <td>English text, basic symbols</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>BCD</td>
                    <td>4 per digit</td>
                    <td>10 (0-9)</td>
                    <td>Calculators, clocks</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>EBCDIC</td>
                    <td>8</td>
                    <td>256</td>
                    <td>IBM mainframes (legacy)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Unicode</td>
                    <td>16+</td>
                    <td>1,000,000+</td>
                    <td>Modern applications, international text, emojis</td>
                </tr>
            </table>

            <p>The Unicode code space is divided into six parts. The first part is for Western alphabets, such as English, Greek, and Russian. The lowest-numbered Unicode characters comprise the ASCII code. The highest provide for user-defined codes.</p>

            <!-- Interactive Character Encoder -->
            <div class="interactive-tool">
                <h4>üîß Interactive Character Encoder</h4>
                <p>See how characters are represented in binary!</p>
                
                <div class="input-group">
                    <label for="charInput">Enter a Character:</label>
                    <input type="text" id="charInput" placeholder="e.g., A" maxlength="1">
                </div>

                <button class="btn" onclick="encodeCharacter()">Encode Character</button>

                <div id="charResult"></div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Glossary -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>üìñ Comprehensive Glossary</h2>
            <p>Master these key terms to excel in data representation!</p>

            <div class="glossary-grid">
                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Bit</strong><br>
                    Binary digit; the smallest unit of data (0 or 1)
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Byte</strong><br>
                    8 bits; standard unit of storage
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Nibble</strong><br>
                    4 bits; half a byte
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Binary</strong><br>
                    Base-2 number system using 0 and 1
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Octal</strong><br>
                    Base-8 number system using digits 0-7
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Decimal</strong><br>
                    Base-10 number system using digits 0-9
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Hexadecimal</strong><br>
                    Base-16 number system using 0-9 and A-F
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Mantissa</strong><br>
                    The fractional part of a floating-point number; also called significand
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Exponent</strong><br>
                    The power of 2 in floating-point representation
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Sign Bit</strong><br>
                    The bit that indicates positive (0) or negative (1)
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Normalization</strong><br>
                    Adjusting a number so there's one non-zero digit before the point
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Overflow</strong><br>
                    When a number is too large to be represented
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Underflow</strong><br>
                    When a number is too small to be represented
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>IEEE 754</strong><br>
                    Standard for floating-point arithmetic
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>One's Complement</strong><br>
                    Method of representing negative numbers by flipping all bits
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Two's Complement</strong><br>
                    Standard method: one's complement + 1
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Sign & Magnitude</strong><br>
                    Using leftmost bit for sign, rest for magnitude
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Parity Bit</strong><br>
                    Extra bit added for error detection
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>ASCII</strong><br>
                    7-bit character encoding standard
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Unicode</strong><br>
                    16-bit+ encoding for international characters
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>BCD</strong><br>
                    Binary-Coded Decimal; 4 bits per decimal digit
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Discrete Data</strong><br>
                    Data from counting (whole numbers)
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Continuous Data</strong><br>
                    Data from measuring (can have fractions)
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Positional Notation</strong><br>
                    System where digit position determines value
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Base/Radix</strong><br>
                    The number of unique digits in a number system
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Precision</strong><br>
                    The number of significant digits that can be represented
                </div>

                <div class="glossary-item">
                    <strong>Bias</strong><br>
                    Value added to exponent (127 for 32-bit floats)
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

